<subSubSection id="DB44225DAD3EACA8997AA0CAF80F53B2" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="66771C724D35A3F97CC0991172F0D396" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D1C9E694D7A3BEB423D445A1A5169472" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Body length: male 14.5-15 mm, female 15.5-16 mm. This is a species with a black body and blackish wings with a large whitish apical wing mark. From similarly coloured species (
<taxonomicName id="A7F03580BF83FD21878626D74E30A526" genus="P." lsidName="P. bispina" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="bispina">
<emphasis id="896237EA8920F04F539D18FFE4C328CD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. bispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="593852D9EE07D79FF032EB2FC2E8EE65" genus="P." lsidName="P. normalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="normalis">
<emphasis id="74AE89E102890F00C72AB3CF84232FD1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. normalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="98D01B16A17DA7437413D22539D682E5" genus="P." lsidName="P. pompiloides" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="pompiloides">
<emphasis id="431DF5365DF527EE9F9D467D062BF9A2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. pompiloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) this species differs by the entirely microtrichose alula.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1D397AD109157E3B051780AE0177861B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="7C7E1A2ACD6990721E22F36C9D3BF3D6" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="46780A1698432435E9C5C6D1E0ACB5A4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The two specimens from Mexico (including the type of 
<taxonomicName id="E3F28B6C8DA6F35A9829954A48FACEF1" genus="P." lsidName="P. niger" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="niger">
<emphasis id="98291E246179EA4DEAB2003072FAE1CD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. niger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) are males, whereas the two specimens from Bolivia (i.e., the type of 
<taxonomicName id="9C1766886A7A6C4ADAEA568E0BACFF15" genus="P." lsidName="P. manni" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="manni">
<emphasis id="14EBFC43BD8FF5751437B344D62A1E86" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. manni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and Peru are both females. Apart from usual sexual dimorphism, no morphological differences could be found. This supports the synonymization of 
<taxonomicName id="1ED2DA5B3986FFE12F18C31E112B0313" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Microdon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Microdon manni" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="manni">
<emphasis id="8B06BF4AA36F4211F056A33F1B5A0997" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Microdon manni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Shannon with 
<taxonomicName id="8F22E4C6A2E56E08E92C8419936EF27A" genus="M." lsidName="M. niger" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="niger">
<emphasis id="56A9347A409B08C9AC5A1151ACDE6D3C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. niger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Williston by 
<bibRefCitation id="D03AB21CDE9279B32D648ADA52A6A924" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.49898" author="Thompson, FC" journalOrPublisher="A catalogue of the Diptera of the Americas south of the United States" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 195" refId="B29" refString="Thompson, FC, Vockeroth, JR, Sedman, YS, 1976. Family Syrphidae. A catalogue of the Diptera of the Americas south of the United States 46: 1 - 195" title="Family Syrphidae." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.49898" volume="46" year="1976">Thompson et al. (1976)</bibRefCitation>
. However, the type localities of these taxa (Bolivia and Mexico, respectively) are far apart, and the types are of opposite sexes. Support for this synonymy would be stronger if males and females of both areas could be compared with each other.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1450B5459CE96000F876DC293569D235" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="9CDC1C2ED8CFB0595A9013D15CE0C088" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5F34A91FD735DD1493FBC64D84BC5160" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Known from southern Mexico and Amazonian parts of Bolivia and Peru.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
